      <h3>What are the differences between a trap and an interrupt? Can traps be generated intentionally by a user program? <span class="ytag">2022</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Trap (Software)</th><th>Interrupt (Hardware)</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Origin</td><td>Generated internally by CPU / software</td><td>Generated externally by hardware device</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Timing</td><td>Synchronous — occurs right after the instruction</td><td>Asynchronous — occurs at unpredictable times</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cause</td><td>System call, division by zero, page fault</td><td>I/O completion, timer tick, keyboard</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Handler</td><td>OS trap handler</td><td>ISR (Interrupt Service Routine)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Example</td><td><code>INT 0x80</code>, <code>SYSCALL</code></td><td>Keyboard interrupt, disk I/O complete</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="def"><strong>Can traps be generated intentionally? YES.</strong> A user program can deliberately trigger a trap using a system call instruction (e.g., <code>INT 0x80</code> on x86 or <code>SYSCALL</code> on x86-64) for the following purposes:
          <ul style="margin-top:8px;">
            <li>To request OS services (read a file, allocate memory, create a process).</li>
            <li>To safely switch from user mode to kernel mode in a controlled manner.</li>
            <li>To perform privileged operations not permitted in user mode.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
