      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <h4>Multiprocessor vs Multicore</h4>
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Multiprocessor System</th><th>Multicore System</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Structure</td><td>Multiple independent CPUs on separate chips</td><td>Multiple cores on a single chip</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Communication</td><td>Via shared memory or bus (slower)</td><td>Via on-chip interconnects (faster)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Power</td><td>Consumes more power</td><td>More power-efficient</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Cost</td><td>More expensive</td><td>Less expensive</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Example</td><td>Server with 4 separate CPUs</td><td>Intel Core i7 with 8 cores</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Multiprogramming</h4>
        <div class="def"><strong>Multiprogramming</strong> is an OS technique where multiple programs are loaded into memory simultaneously and share the CPU. When one process waits for I/O, the OS switches the CPU to another ready process — keeping the CPU busy at all times. This significantly increases CPU utilisation and system throughput.<br><br>
        <strong>Example:</strong> While Process A waits for disk I/O, Process B runs on the CPU.</div>
      </div>
