  <div class="qcard open reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>Define Thread. List benefits of multi-threading. Demonstrate the three methods to implement Threads in Java. <span class="ytag">2024</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="def"><strong>Thread:</strong> The smallest unit of execution within a process. A lightweight sub-process that shares the same memory space (code, data, heap) as its parent process but executes independently with its own stack and program counter.</div>
        <h4>Benefits of Multithreading</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Improved Performance:</strong> Concurrent execution utilises multiple CPU cores efficiently, reducing total time.</li>
          <li><strong>Resource Sharing:</strong> Threads share the process's memory space, enabling easy data sharing and lower overhead than IPC.</li>
          <li><strong>Responsiveness:</strong> The application remains responsive (e.g., a GUI thread continues while a background thread processes data).</li>
          <li><strong>Faster Creation:</strong> Threads are lighter than processes — creation and context switching are much faster.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Method 1 — Extending Thread class</h4>
        <pre><span class="kw">class</span> MyThread <span class="kw">extends</span> Thread {
    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">run</span>() {
        System.out.<span class="fn">println</span>(<span class="str">"Thread via Thread class"</span>);
    }
    <span class="kw">public static void</span> <span class="fn">main</span>(String[] args) {
        <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="fn">MyThread</span>().<span class="fn">start</span>();
    }
}</pre>
        <h4>Method 2 — Implementing Runnable interface</h4>
        <pre><span class="kw">class</span> MyRun <span class="kw">implements</span> Runnable {
    <span class="kw">public void</span> <span class="fn">run</span>() {
        System.out.<span class="fn">println</span>(<span class="str">"Thread via Runnable"</span>);
    }
    <span class="kw">public static void</span> <span class="fn">main</span>(String[] a) {
        <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="fn">Thread</span>(<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="fn">MyRun</span>()).<span class="fn">start</span>();
    }
}</pre>
        <h4>Method 3 — Using Callable with ExecutorService</h4>
        <pre><span class="kw">class</span> MyCall <span class="kw">implements</span> Callable&lt;String&gt; {
    <span class="kw">public</span> String <span class="fn">call</span>() { <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="str">"Thread via Callable"</span>; }
    <span class="kw">public static void</span> <span class="fn">main</span>(String[] a) <span class="kw">throws</span> Exception {
        ExecutorService ex = Executors.<span class="fn">newSingleThreadExecutor</span>();
        System.out.<span class="fn">println</span>(ex.<span class="fn">submit</span>(<span class="kw">new</span> <span class="fn">MyCall</span>()).<span class="fn">get</span>());
        ex.<span class="fn">shutdown</span>();
    }
}</pre>
