  <!-- Q2 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>Differentiate between User Level Thread and Kernel Level Thread. Describe actions taken by kernel to context switch between kernel-level threads. <span class="ytag">2024</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>User Level Thread (ULT)</th><th>Kernel Level Thread (KLT)</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Management</td><td>Managed by user-level library; OS unaware</td><td>Managed directly by OS kernel</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Speed</td><td>Faster creation and context switching</td><td>Slower — requires kernel mode transition</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Multiprocessor</td><td>Cannot exploit multiple CPUs simultaneously</td><td>Can run on different CPUs in parallel</td></tr>
          <tr><td>If one thread blocks</td><td>All threads in the process block</td><td>Other threads continue running</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Examples</td><td>POSIX Pthreads (user-space)</td><td>Windows threads, Linux pthreads (kernel)</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Context Switching Between Kernel Threads</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Step 1 — Save current thread:</strong> Store CPU registers, program counter, and stack pointer into the current thread's Thread Control Block (TCB). Update state to BLOCKED or READY.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 2 — Select next thread:</strong> Scheduler picks the next thread from the ready queue based on the scheduling policy (priority, round-robin, etc.).</li>
          <li><strong>Step 3 — Restore new thread:</strong> Load registers, program counter, and stack pointer from the new thread's TCB. Update state to RUNNING and transfer CPU execution.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

