      <span class="qbadge m3">3 Marks</span>
      <h3>Explain address binding. Explain the various address binding schemes. <span class="ytag">2022</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="def"><strong>Address Binding:</strong> The process of mapping a logical address (generated by a program) to a physical address in main memory. It is crucial for the correct execution of programs.</div>
        <h4>Three Binding Schemes</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Compile-time Binding:</strong> Addresses are fixed at compile time. Produces absolute code. Inflexible — the entire program must reside at a fixed memory location. If that location changes, the code must be recompiled.</li>
          <li><strong>Load-time Binding:</strong> Addresses are resolved when the program is loaded into memory. The compiler generates relocatable code; the loader assigns actual addresses at load time.</li>
          <li><strong>Execution-time (Run-time) Binding:</strong> Addresses are translated at runtime using the MMU (Memory Management Unit). Allows dynamic relocation and supports virtual memory. The most flexible scheme, used by modern OS.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

