        </table>
        <h4>Swapping and System Efficiency</h4>
        <div class="def">
          <strong>Improvements:</strong> Swapping increases the degree of multiprogramming — more processes can be active, improving CPU utilisation and overall throughput.<br><br>
          <strong>Degradations:</strong> Swapping requires significant CPU time, disk I/O, and memory management overhead. Excessive swapping causes <em>thrashing</em>, where more time is spent swapping than executing processes.<br><br>
          <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Yes, swapping can be used in multiprogramming to manage memory efficiently — processes not actively using the CPU are swapped to disk, freeing RAM for active ones. The benefit must be balanced against the swapping overhead.
        </div>
