  <div class="unit-body">

  <!-- Q1 -->
  <div class="qcard open reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>State and explain the necessary and sufficient conditions for a deadlock. What do you understand by deadlock and livelock? Discuss the Banker's Algorithm. <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="note">ALL four conditions must hold simultaneously for a deadlock to occur.</div>
        <h4>Four Necessary Conditions</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mutual Exclusion:</strong> At least one resource is held in a non-shareable mode — only one process can use it at a time.</li>
          <li><strong>Hold and Wait:</strong> A process holds at least one resource and is waiting to acquire additional resources currently held by other processes.</li>
          <li><strong>No Preemption:</strong> Resources cannot be forcibly taken from a process. They are released only voluntarily when the process is done.</li>
          <li><strong>Circular Wait:</strong> A circular chain P1→P2→P3→P1 where each process waits for a resource held by the next process in the chain.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Deadlock vs Livelock</h4>
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Deadlock</th><th>Livelock</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Processes are blocked permanently — no progress at all</td><td>Processes keep changing state in response to each other but make no real progress</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Processes do nothing — stuck waiting</td><td>Processes are actively "trying" but never succeed</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Example: two trains blocking each other on a single track</td><td>Example: two people stepping aside in the same direction to let the other pass, indefinitely</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Banker's Algorithm</h4>
        <div class="def">A <strong>deadlock avoidance</strong> algorithm that ensures the system never enters an unsafe state by checking resource allocation requests before granting them.
          <ul style="margin-top:10px;">
            <li><strong>Data structures:</strong> Available[], Allocation[][], Max[][], Need[][] where Need = Max − Allocation.</li>
            <li><strong>On request:</strong> Check if Need[i] ≤ Available. If not, make the process wait.</li>
            <li><strong>Safety check:</strong> Tentatively allocate → find a safe sequence → if a safe sequence exists, grant. Otherwise, the process must wait.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q2 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>Describe the techniques for recovery from deadlock. Explain the Resource Allocation Graph (RAG) with examples. <span class="ytag">2023</span> <span class="ytag">2024</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <h4>Deadlock Recovery Techniques</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Process Termination — Abort All:</strong> All deadlocked processes terminated at once. Simple and effective but wasteful — all their work is lost.</li>
          <li><strong>Process Termination — Abort One at a Time:</strong> Terminate one process, check if deadlock is resolved, repeat. Minimises data loss but incurs more overhead per cycle.</li>
          <li><strong>Resource Preemption:</strong> Resources are forcibly taken from some processes and given to others until the deadlock breaks. Must decide which resource to preempt and handle rollback. Risk: starvation — same process may always be chosen as the victim.</li>
          <li><strong>Process Rollback:</strong> Roll back a deadlocked process to a previously saved safe state (using checkpoints). Can be total (restart from beginning) or partial (rollback to nearest checkpoint).</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Resource Allocation Graph (RAG)</h4>
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Component</th><th>Representation</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Process</td><td>Circle (P1, P2…)</td><td>A running or waiting process</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Resource</td><td>Rectangle (R1, R2…)</td><td>A system resource (CPU, memory, I/O)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Request Edge</td><td>P → R</td><td>Process is requesting the resource</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Assignment Edge</td><td>R → P</td><td>Resource is assigned to the process</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="def">
          <strong>No Deadlock:</strong> P1→R1→P2→R2 — no cycle → no deadlock.<br>
          <strong>Deadlock:</strong> P1→R1→P2→R2→P1 — cycle exists → deadlock!
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q3 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>Compare Deadlock Prevention and Deadlock Avoidance. Can a system be in a state that is neither deadlocked nor safe? Give an example. <span class="ytag">2024</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Deadlock Prevention</th><th>Deadlock Avoidance</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Approach</td><td>Eliminates one of the 4 necessary conditions permanently</td><td>Dynamically checks if granting a request keeps the system safe</td></tr>
          <tr><td>How</td><td>Violate: Mutual Exclusion / Hold&Wait / No Preemption / Circular Wait</td><td>Uses Banker's Algorithm to check for a safe state before granting</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Conservatism</td><td>Very conservative — may deny safe requests</td><td>Less conservative; better resource utilisation</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Overhead</td><td>Low runtime overhead</td><td>High — requires advance knowledge of maximum resource needs</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Examples</td><td>Require all resources at once; impose resource ordering</td><td>Banker's Algorithm; RAG with claim edges</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Unsafe State — Neither Deadlocked nor Safe</h4>
        <div class="def"><strong>Yes — this is called an Unsafe State.</strong> An unsafe state is NOT currently deadlocked, but future resource requests MAY lead to deadlock.
          <br><br>
          <strong>Example:</strong> 3 processes, 10 resource instances total:
        </div>
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Process</th><th>Allocated</th><th>Maximum</th><th>Still Needs</th></tr>
          <tr><td>P1</td><td>3</td><td>7</td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td>P2</td><td>2</td><td>4</td><td>2</td></tr>
          <tr><td>P3</td><td>3</td><td>6</td><td>3</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="note">Available = 10 − (3+2+3) = 2 resources. P2 can finish (needs 2), releases 4. But if P1 or P3 requests first, neither can satisfy their need with only 2 available — deadlock risk. <strong>Not currently deadlocked, but UNSAFE.</strong></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q4 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m4">4 Marks</span>
      <h3>Clearly justify why deadlocks cannot arise in a bounded buffer producer-consumer system. <span class="ytag">2022</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="def">Deadlocks cannot arise because none of the four necessary deadlock conditions hold simultaneously:</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No Circular Wait (key reason):</strong> Producer waits only when buffer is FULL; consumer waits only when buffer is EMPTY. They never simultaneously wait for each other — circular wait is impossible.</li>
          <li><strong>No Hold and Wait:</strong> Producer only adds to the buffer when space exists and does not hold a slot while waiting for another. Consumer only takes when data exists.</li>
          <li><strong>Orderly Resource Allocation:</strong> Mutual exclusion is managed so only one process modifies the buffer at a time, preventing the circular hold-and-wait pattern.</li>
          <li><strong>At least one can always progress:</strong> If the buffer is neither full nor empty, both can operate. At least one (producer or consumer) can always make progress.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

