      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>What is the difference between fixed and variable partition? Explain the need of compaction. <span class="ytag">2023</span> <span class="ytag">2024</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Fixed Partition</th><th>Variable Partition</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Partition Size</td><td>Predefined, fixed-size blocks</td><td>Dynamically allocated per process size</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fragmentation</td><td>Internal (unused space inside allocated block)</td><td>External (free memory in small scattered holes)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Flexibility</td><td>Not flexible — sizes set at system startup</td><td>Flexible — partition created at runtime per need</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Memory Utilisation</td><td>Wastes memory if process &lt; partition</td><td>Better — partition matches process size</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Number of Processes</td><td>Limited by number of fixed partitions</td><td>Limited only by available free memory</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Implementation</td><td>Simple</td><td>Complex memory management required</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Need for Compaction</h4>
        <div class="def"><strong>Problem:</strong> In variable partitioning, as processes load and terminate, free memory fragments into many small non-contiguous blocks. Even if total free memory is sufficient, a large process cannot be loaded because no single contiguous block is large enough.<br><br>
          <strong>Compaction</strong> = moving all active processes to one end of memory, merging all free fragments into one large contiguous block.<br>
          <strong>Benefit:</strong> Large processes can now be accommodated.<br>
          <strong>Drawback:</strong> Expensive — requires relocating all active processes; processes must be stoppable and address-rebindable at execution time.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

