      <h3>What is Belady's Anomaly? Why do LRU and Optimal Page Replacement not suffer from it? <span class="ytag">2024</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="def"><strong>Belady's Anomaly:</strong> The counterintuitive phenomenon in FIFO page replacement where increasing the number of page frames causes MORE page faults instead of fewer.</div>
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Frames</th><th>Algorithm</th><th>Page Faults</th></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td>FIFO</td><td>9</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td>FIFO</td><td class="lo">10 ← MORE faults with more frames!</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td>LRU</td><td class="hi">Not affected</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td>Optimal</td><td class="hi">Not affected</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Why LRU and Optimal are Immune</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stack Property:</strong> Both LRU and Optimal are stack algorithms — the set of pages in memory with n frames is always a subset of pages with n+1 frames. Adding frames always helps.</li>
          <li><strong>LRU:</strong> Replaces the least recently used page. More frames means we always keep recently used pages → fewer or equal faults.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimal:</strong> Replaces the page not used for the longest future time. More frames → always holds the best possible set → fewer or equal faults.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

