  <!-- Q7 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>What is physical vs logical address space? What are the benefits of Segmentation? <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Physical Address</th><th>Logical Address</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Also called</td><td>Absolute / Real address</td><td>Virtual address</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Generated by</td><td>Memory hardware (RAM)</td><td>CPU during instruction execution</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Value</td><td>Actual location in RAM</td><td>Relative — independent of physical location</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Size</td><td>Limited by RAM installed</td><td>Can be larger than physical memory</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Visible to</td><td>Memory hardware</td><td>Process; translated to physical by MMU</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Example</td><td>0x0A4B5C (real RAM location)</td><td>0x0010 (virtual, mapped by OS)</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Benefits of Segmentation</h4>
        <div class="def">Segmentation divides a program's address space into variable-sized logical units called segments (code, data, stack, heap). Each segment has a base address and limit stored in the segment table.</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Logical Organisation:</strong> Segments correspond to natural program modules, making the memory layout easier for programmers to understand and protect.</li>
          <li><strong>Sharing:</strong> Segments can be shared between processes (e.g., a shared library segment) without duplicating code.</li>
          <li><strong>Protection:</strong> Different access rights per segment (code = read-only, data = read-write), preventing accidental code modification.</li>
          <li><strong>Dynamic Growth:</strong> Segments grow independently (stack grows separately from heap) without affecting other segments.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q8 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m4">4 Marks</span>
      <h3>Demand paging: disk access = 20ms, memory access = 1μs, TLB hit rate = 80%, page fault rate = 2%. Find effective memory access time. <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <h4>Given Data</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Disk access time = 20 ms = 20,000 μs</li>
          <li>Main memory access = 1 μs per access</li>
          <li>TLB hit rate = 80% → TLB miss = 20%</li>
          <li>Page table = 2 memory accesses (without TLB)</li>
          <li>Page fault rate = 2%</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>EAT Formula</h4>
        <div class="def">
          EAT = (TLB hit % × 1 access) + (Page table hit % × 2 accesses) + (Page fault % × disk access)<br><br>
          EAT = (0.80 × 1) + (0.18 × 2) + (0.02 × 20,001)<br>
          EAT = 0.80 + 0.36 + 400.02<br>
          <strong>EAT ≈ 401.18 μs</strong>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

