      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>Differentiate between a file and a Directory. Justify the need of file system. <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>File</th><th>Directory</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Definition</td><td>Collection of related data stored on a storage device</td><td>Container holding files and other directories</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Also called</td><td>Document, program, data file</td><td>Folder</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Extension</td><td>Has a name and extension (e.g., data.txt)</td><td>No extension typically</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Content</td><td>Text, images, programs, binary data</td><td>File names and their metadata/pointers</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Operations</td><td>Read, write, append, delete, rename</td><td>Create, delete, list, rename</td></tr>
        </table>
        <h4>Need for File System</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Organisation:</strong> Provides a structured way to store, name, and locate files in a hierarchy. Without a file system, data would be an unorganised mass of bytes on disk.</li>
          <li><strong>Data Integrity:</strong> Implements error-checking and journaling to protect files from corruption, power failures, and data loss.</li>
          <li><strong>Storage Management:</strong> Manages allocation and deallocation of storage space efficiently, tracking free and used blocks on disk.</li>
          <li><strong>Access Control &amp; Protection:</strong> Enforces permissions (read/write/execute for owner/group/others), preventing unauthorised access to sensitive files.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q2 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m3">3 Marks</span>
      <h3>Explain the main features of general graph directory structure. <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="def">A <strong>general graph directory structure</strong> allows multiple parent directories for a single file — unlike a tree where each file has exactly one parent.</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Nodes:</strong> Represent files or directories.</li>
          <li><strong>Edges:</strong> Directed edges represent parent-child relationships.</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple Parents (Hard Links):</strong> A file can appear in multiple directories, saving space by avoiding duplication of data.</li>
          <li><strong>Cycles possible:</strong> Can create circular references; OS must handle with reference counting or garbage collection cycle detection.</li>
          <li><strong>Example:</strong> Unix/Linux uses general graph directories — hard links allow a file to exist in multiple directory locations simultaneously.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Q3 -->
  <div class="qcard reveal">
    <div class="qcard-hdr" onclick="toggleQ(this)">
      <span class="qbadge m3">3 Marks</span>
      <h3>Should the OS maintain a separate open file table for each user or one table? If the same file is accessed by two programs, should there be separate entries? <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="def"><strong>Recommended — Hybrid Model:</strong>
          <ul style="margin-top:8px;">
            <li><strong>Master Open File Table (system-wide):</strong> One entry per unique open file; contains file metadata, disk location, lock information.</li>
            <li><strong>Per-Process Open File Table:</strong> Each process has its own table with entries pointing to the master table; stores process-specific info: file position/offset, open mode (r/w), access rights.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="note"><strong>Same file, two programs:</strong> Yes — separate entries in the per-process table, both pointing to the same master table entry. Each program needs its own file position pointer (one may be at byte 100, the other at byte 500) and its own access mode.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

