      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>What do you understand by disk scheduling? Describe seek time and rotational latency. Describe SCAN scheduling. How is C-SCAN different from SCAN? <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <div class="def"><strong>Disk Scheduling:</strong> A technique for determining the order to service pending disk I/O requests to minimise total seek time and improve throughput.</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Seek Time:</strong> Time for the disk arm/head to move from its current cylinder to the target cylinder. The most significant component of disk access time, measured in milliseconds.</li>
          <li><strong>Rotational Latency:</strong> Time for the disk to rotate until the target sector is under the read/write head. Average rotational latency = ½ × (1/RPM) × 60 seconds.</li>
          <li><strong>Transfer Time:</strong> Time to actually transfer data — depends on rotation speed and data size.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>SCAN vs C-SCAN</h4>
        <table class="tbl">
          <tr><th>Feature</th><th>SCAN (Elevator)</th><th>C-SCAN (Circular SCAN)</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Head movement</td><td>Moves from one end to the other, then reverses</td><td>Moves to one end, jumps to other end, resumes in same direction</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Direction</td><td>Alternates: forward then backward</td><td>Always moves in one direction only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fairness</td><td>Requests near mid-disk served more often</td><td>More uniform waiting time for all cylinders</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Starvation</td><td>Possible for cylinders at ends</td><td>Less starvation — all areas served equally</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Example</td><td>Head at 50, goes to 199, reverses to 0</td><td>Head at 50, goes to 199, jumps to 0, goes to 50</td></tr>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

