      <span class="qbadge m7">7 Marks</span>
      <h3>Write short notes on (any three): Microkernel, Banker's Algorithm, Process Control Block, Paging, Indexed Allocation. <span class="ytag">2019</span></h3>
      <span class="qtog">▼</span>
    </div>
    <div class="qbody">
      <div class="ans">
        <h4>(a) Microkernel</h4>
        <div class="def">A minimal OS kernel providing only the most essential services: process management, memory management, and inter-process communication (IPC). All other services (file systems, device drivers, networking) run as user-space server processes.
          <ul style="margin-top:8px;">
            <li><strong>Key features:</strong> Small size, modular, flexible, more reliable and secure (a crash in a server doesn't crash the kernel).</li>
            <li><strong>Examples:</strong> Mach, QNX, L4, MINIX.</li>
            <li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> More IPC overhead compared to monolithic kernels because servers must communicate through message passing.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h4>(b) Banker's Algorithm</h4>
        <div class="def">A deadlock avoidance algorithm that ensures the system never enters an unsafe state.
          <ul style="margin-top:8px;">
            <li><strong>Data structures:</strong> Available[], Allocation[][], Max[][], Need[][] (Need = Max − Allocation).</li>
            <li><strong>Safety check:</strong> Find a safe sequence — process whose Need ≤ Available → let it finish → release resources → repeat.</li>
            <li><strong>Grant request only if:</strong> Request[i] ≤ Need[i] AND resulting state is SAFE.</li>
            <li><strong>Limitation:</strong> Requires advance knowledge of each process's maximum resource needs.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h4>(c) Paging</h4>
        <div class="def">Memory management technique dividing physical memory into fixed-size <em>frames</em> and logical memory into <em>pages</em> of the same size.
          <ul style="margin-top:8px;">
            <li>CPU generates logical address → (page number, offset) → page table lookup → physical address (frame number, offset).</li>
            <li>Eliminates external fragmentation; supports non-contiguous memory allocation.</li>
            <li>The page table maps page numbers to frame numbers; maintained by the OS.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <h4>(d) Indexed Allocation</h4>
        <div class="def">A disk allocation method where each file has an index block containing pointers to all its data blocks.
          <ul style="margin-top:8px;">
            <li>Supports direct random access to any block via the index block.</li>
            <li>No external fragmentation; files can grow without data blocks being contiguous.</li>
            <li>If the index block is lost or corrupted, the entire file is inaccessible.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
